{"id": 12, "ts": 1778777188.317063, "event": "public_discussion_message", "round": 1, "agent": "agent_3", "message": "Based on the attributes we have, I see the following trade\u2011offs:\n- **Candidate\u202fA** shows strong situational awareness (anticipates danger, sees complex connections, excellent spatial vision) and good leadership, but the unfriendly demeanor and unhealthy eating raise concerns about crew interaction and fitness for long\u2011duration flights. We have no data on his stress resilience.\n- **Candidate\u202fB** is very conscientious, handles stress well, and is skilled at assessing weather\u2014key technical competencies for long\u2011haul operations. He also has excellent computer skills. The downsides are his pretentiousness, occasional wrong tone, and a tendency to be uncooperative or make nasty remarks, which could impair teamwork.\n- **Candidate\u202fC** makes quick, correct decisions, has excellent attention, puts others\u2019 concerns first, and creates a positive atmosphere with the crew. However, he struggles to communicate ideas, is seen as egocentric, and is not eager to pursue further education\u2014issues that could affect both safety communication and long\u2011term development.\n- **Candidate\u202fD** concentrates well, solves problems extremely well, takes responsibility seriously, and responds adequately to unexpected events\u2014strong indicators of reliability and judgment. Yet he is considered moody, a loner, arrogant, and has weak leadership, all of which undermine crew cooperation.\nFor a long\u2011distance pilot, the ability to stay calm under pressure, make sound decisions, and reliably manage technical aspects (weather, navigation) is paramount, while teamwork and communication are also essential. Candidate\u202fB offers the most robust combination of stress resilience, conscientiousness, and technical competence, even though his interpersonal style is a concern. The other candidates either lack critical stress/technical